<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-991-190  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 991 190.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  Dec 14 1989 n1194 p26(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Putting a business stamp on it. (automating the British postoffice)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ernest-Jones, Terry.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The information technology (IT) chief at the British Post Officespent years getting the board to move on making informationtechnology the cornerstone of its corporate strategy.andP;  Computerautomation had been largely an afterthought in the 300-year-oldinstitution's business plan.andP;  The Post Office is now committed tospend 75 million pounds a year on IT upgrades in the system.andP;  TheIT chief sold his bosses on his IT strategy partly because hepresented it in business terms, leaving out the technologicaljargon.andP;  IT planning has to grow out of business planning.andO;Competition from outside mail delivery companies spurred the boardto automate Datapost delivery service.andP;  A closer relationshipneeds to be established between IT people and business people inthe organization.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United KingdomPostal ServiceAutomationBusiness Planning.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>